['[Justitia Hong Kong Manifesto]', 'In the two decades since Hong Kong’s (‘HK’) handover from the United Kingdom to the People’s Republic of China (‘PRC’) in 1997, the PRC has repeatedly violated the Sino-British Joint Declaration and severely cracked down on civil liberties that were once promised to Hong Kongers. With substantial collusion between the Chinese central government, HK government and pro-Beijing politicians which culminated in a complete manipulation of the Basic Law, the Chinese Communist Party has weaponised the Executive, Legislative and Judicial bodies to politically persecute pro-democracy activists in HK. This has led, and will continue to lead, to a mass exodus of HK émigrés. There is now an urgent need to support exiled HK activists, to develop a HK community in the U.K., to promote the unique HK identity, to facilitate Hong Kongers’ integration into British society and to continue HK’s activism abroad. We aspire to achieve all of these goals.', 'Our founding members come from a variety of different backgrounds. From the front lines of the 2019 HK protests to overseas participants in the West, we are united by pro-democracy ideals and the betterment of HK.', 'We believe that the promises granted by the Sino-British Joint Declaration to HK and its people must be kept. In the years since the Handover, Chinese forces have unilaterally violated this international treaty and made repeated attempts to undermine its validity. From interference in HK’s affairs and reneging on universal suffrage to violent crackdowns by the HK Police Force and enactment of the draconian National Security Law to politically persecute HK activists, China has shown time again its unwillingness to play by its own rules. Justitia implores the UK Government to take a much stronger stance with China, including targeted Magnitsky sanctions against HK and PRC government officials responsible for the continued erosion of HK’s civil liberties and rule of law.', 'The pro-democracy movement in HK was founded on the spirit and respect for differing opinions on direction and strategy. Justitia continues to embrace said diversity and shall maintain frequent dialogue with exiled activists. ['The Consulate General of Canada in Hong Kong invites you to join us at the Canadian Commemorative Ceremony to mark the 75th Anniversary of the Battle of Hong Kong.', '', 'The ceremony has been held each year since 1947 to commemorate the Canadian soldiers who died in Hong Kong during the Second World War. Over 550 Canadians of the two regiments that were sent to Hong Kong, the Winnipeg Grenadiers and the Royal Rifles of Canada, gave their lives in defence of the island. Their sacrifice remains one of the most significant chapters in Canada’s history and constitutes a vivid expression of the important ties which unite Canada and Hong Kong.', '', 'We are honoured to be joined by veterans of the Second World War, leading members of the Canadian community in Hong Kong and Macao, the Canadian Scouts, the Hong Kong Adventure Corps and students from the four Canadian curriculum schools in Hong Kong and Macao.', '', 'The ceremony is open to all and the Consulate General of Canada in Hong Kong welcomes you to join in the commemoration of the brave soldiers.']
